            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Friedman\u2019s story is one of Oakland grit forged into San Francisco success. Raised in the Laurel district of Oakland by a Black union electrician father and a white, Jewish mother who taught high school English, David\u2019s upbringing was a blend of practical know-how and intellectual curiosity. He learned the value of a hard day's work from his father and a love for complex narratives from his mother, a combination that would define his professional life.\n\nHe enrolled in the Business Administration program at Cal State East Bay, but his formal education was cut short. When his father suffered a debilitating back injury, 20-year-old David left school to help support his family. This became his crucial turning point. He took an entry-level job as a processor\u2019s assistant at a mortgage brokerage, a world he knew nothing about. But David was a voracious learner and a natural with people. He saw the loan officers' success and decided that would be his path, with or without a degree. He got licensed and proceeded to outwork everyone, blessed with an innate ability to translate complex financial jargon into hopeful plans for aspiring homeowners.\n\nNow, at 41, David is a Senior Mortgage Loan Officer in the heart of San Francisco\u2019s Financial District, a respected figure who earned his $225,000 income through sheer tenacity. His daily routine begins before sunrise, catching an early BART train from his sleek condo near Lake Merritt for the 12.5-mile commute. That ride is his quiet time\u2014a mix of finance podcasts and old-school soul music.\n\nHis twenties were dedicated to his career, a focus that contributed to an amicable divorce in his early thirties. Today, his social life is more balanced, revolving around a tight-knit group of friends from Oakland and a few industry colleagues. He enjoys weekend hikes in the Redwood Regional Park and exploring San Francisco's incredible restaurant scene on carefully planned dates.\n\nDavid\u2019s connection to San Francisco is professional; it\u2019s the arena where he tests his skills. But his heart remains in Oakland. His ultimate dream is to open his own brokerage firm there, creating opportunities for smart, hungry individuals who, like him, may have taken an unconventional path. For David, success isn't just the commission check; it's the profound satisfaction of handing someone the keys to their first home, a tangible piece of the dream he built for himself."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was ten, sitting on the linoleum floor of their Laurel district kitchen. His father, smelling of copper wire and sweat, was carefully soldering a frayed lamp cord, his large hands surprisingly delicate. Across the table, his mother\u2019s voice was a steady rhythm as she read aloud from *A Tale of Two Cities*. In that moment, David understood that there were two ways to make things whole: with your hands and with a story. It was a lesson in practicality and narrative that he would carry forever.\n\n2.\nThe memory that truly forged him was seeing his father, a man of immense physical pride, wince trying to lift a glass of water from his bedside table. It was a few weeks after the injury. David, home from Cal State for the weekend, saw the flicker of shame in his dad\u2019s eyes. In that silent exchange, the decision was made. The weight of his family\u2019s future settled onto his 20-year-old shoulders, extinguishing the carelessness of youth and replacing it with a cold, clear sense of purpose.\n\n3.\nHis first \"impossible\" closing, around age 24. It was for a young couple, an auto mechanic and a preschool teacher, who had been rejected twice. David spent weeks restructuring their finances, finding a little-known loan program. He\u2019ll never forget the wife\u2019s gasp when he handed her the keys. It wasn\u2019t the commission; it was the visceral transfer of hope into reality. That day, he stopped seeing his job as selling loans and started seeing it as building legacies, one family at a time.\n\n4.\nThe end of his marriage wasn't a fight, but a quiet conversation on their Lake Merritt apartment balcony. His wife, whom he still respected immensely, told him, \"David, you're building an empire, but I need a partner to build a life with.\" There was no anger, only a profound sadness. Her words hit him with the force of a market crash, revealing the personal debt he\u2019d accrued while chasing professional success. It was the humbling lesson that made him seek a more balanced portfolio in life.\n\n5.\nTwo years ago, he drove to a small house in West Oakland to meet his clients\u2014a single mother who worked two jobs. He handed her the keys, and she just stared at them in her palm and started to cry. Looking at her, he saw the mirror of his own hunger, his own unconventional path. The Financial District skyscrapers felt a million miles away. This was real. This was the reason for the early BART rides and the late nights. It cemented his dream: to come home and build this feeling for his own community."
